      "content": "```json\n{\n  \"id\": \"toolu_01UcQTBRUACqyoxQD1mPu82b\",\n  \"name\": \"filesystem\",\n  \"content\": \"# Blueprint: Humbug\\n\\n## What is Humbug?\\n\\nHumbug is an **operating system for human-AI collaboration** \\u2014 a modular, extensible platform\\nthat lets humans and AIs work together on ideas, projects, and software.\\n\\nIt is not a chatbot wrapper, a coding assistant plugin, or a thin shell around an AI API.\\nIt is a full collaboration environment in which both humans and AIs are first-class actors,\\nwith equal access to the same tools and UI capabilities.\\n\\n## Who is it for?\\n\\nHumbug is designed for anyone who needs to work with AIs on complex, multi-step tasks:\\n\\n- **Developers** building and maintaining software\\n- **Researchers** exploring ideas and analysing information\\n- **General users** who want to collaborate with AIs on any kind of project\\n\\nThe mindspace concept means every project \\u2014 whether software, writing, research, or\\nsomething else entirely \\u2014 gets its own persistent, isolated environment.\\n\\n## Core principles\\n\\n### Humans and AIs are equal actors\\nAll tools, including the GUI, are designed to be usable by both humans and AIs.\\nThere is no separate \\\"AI mode\\\" \\u2014 the same environment serves both.\\n\\n### Conversations drive agentic workflows\\nThe conversation is the primary unit of collaboration.\\nAIs discover what they need, edit content, run tools, and orchestrate the UI \\u2014 all from\\nwithin a conversation, without requiring a separate orchestration layer.\\n\\n### Transparency over automation\\nHumbug does not hide what is happening.\\nEvery tool call, approval request, and AI action is visible to the user.\\nThe human-in-the-loop is a design feature, not an afterthought.\\nThis gives users the ability to catch problems early and course-correct before they\\nbecome expensive mistakes.\\n\\n### Minimal dependencies, maximum understandability\\nHumbug follows the pattern of an OS kernel: simple, largely self-contained, and\\ncomprehensible from a single repository.\\nOnly 4 external runtime dependencies exist beyond the Python standard library.\\nBoth humans and AIs should be able to understand almost every part of the system.\\n\\n### Vendor independence\\nHumbug supports many AI backends (Anthropic, DeepSeek, Google, Mistral, Ollama, OpenAI,\\nvLLM, xAI, Z.ai) and is designed to make it easy to add more.\\nUsers are never locked in to a single provider.\\n\\n### Bootstrapped development\\nEach version of Humbug has been built using the previous version.\\nThis means the software is both a product and a proof-of-concept: it demonstrates what\\nhuman-AI collaboration can achieve at scale.\\nOver 90% of the code has been written by LLMs working within Humbug itself.\\n\\n### Clean, modular architecture\\nThe codebase is held to strict standards: mypy type checking, pylint linting, and a\\ndependency rules system that prevents unwanted coupling between modules.\\nThis discipline is what makes it possible for AIs to reliably modify and extend the code.\\n\\nThe dependency rules enforce a strict separation between top-level modules.\\nThe dependency graph must be acyclic \\u2014 no module may depend on another that depends (directly\\nor transitively) on it.\\nThis ensures each module can be reasoned about, tested, and evolved independently.\\nIt also prevents the kind of gradual coupling that is especially risky when LLMs are\\ncontributing code, since an AI might otherwise introduce a convenience import that silently\\ncreates a circular dependency between modules.\\n\\n## What Humbug is NOT\\n\\n- **Not a replacement for the OS.** Humbug runs on top of Windows, macOS, and Linux\\n  and provides OS-like abstractions without replacing the underlying system.\\n- **Not just a developer tool.** While it has strong support for software development,\\n  it is designed for any activity where humans and AIs need to work together.\\n- **Not a walled garden.** It is open-source and designed to be extended.\\n- **Not a single-AI system.** Multiple AI conversations can run simultaneously, with\\n  support for task delegation between AI instances.\\n\\n## Menai: a language designed for AIs\\n\\nPreviously, programming languages were designed for human developers.\\nWhile AIs are proficient with most of these languages, they can be unsafe because they\\nsupport potentially dangerous I/O operations.\\n\\nMenai is a pure, functional, Lisp-inspired language designed specifically for AI use.\\nBeing side-effect free, it requires no sandboxing and no user approval to execute.\\nThis lets AIs build and run complex algorithmic tools freely and safely, without\\ninterrupting the human collaborator.\\n\\nMenai supports higher-order functions, tail-call optimisation, strict numeric typing,\\nand a rich standard library. It is compiled to bytecode and executed by a C VM for\\nperformance, with a Python VM fallback.\\n\\n\",\n  \"error\": null\n}\n```\n`content` is:\n```markdown\n# Blueprint: Humbug\n\n## What is Humbug?\n\nHumbug is an **operating system for human-AI collaboration** \u2014 a modular, extensible platform\nthat lets humans and AIs work together on ideas, projects, and software.\n\nIt is not a chatbot wrapper, a coding assistant plugin, or a thin shell around an AI API.\nIt is a full collaboration environment in which both humans and AIs are first-class actors,\nwith equal access to the same tools and UI capabilities.\n\n## Who is it for?\n\nHumbug is designed for anyone who needs to work with AIs on complex, multi-step tasks:\n\n- **Developers** building and maintaining software\n- **Researchers** exploring ideas and analysing information\n- **General users** who want to collaborate with AIs on any kind of project\n\nThe mindspace concept means every project \u2014 whether software, writing, research, or\nsomething else entirely \u2014 gets its own persistent, isolated environment.\n\n## Core principles\n\n### Humans and AIs are equal actors\nAll tools, including the GUI, are designed to be usable by both humans and AIs.\nThere is no separate \"AI mode\" \u2014 the same environment serves both.\n\n### Conversations drive agentic workflows\nThe conversation is the primary unit of collaboration.\nAIs discover what they need, edit content, run tools, and orchestrate the UI \u2014 all from\nwithin a conversation, without requiring a separate orchestration layer.\n\n### Transparency over automation\nHumbug does not hide what is happening.\nEvery tool call, approval request, and AI action is visible to the user.\nThe human-in-the-loop is a design feature, not an afterthought.\nThis gives users the ability to catch problems early and course-correct before they\nbecome expensive mistakes.\n\n### Minimal dependencies, maximum understandability\nHumbug follows the pattern of an OS kernel: simple, largely self-contained, and\ncomprehensible from a single repository.\nOnly 4 external runtime dependencies exist beyond the Python standard library.\nBoth humans and AIs should be able to understand almost every part of the system.\n\n### Vendor independence\nHumbug supports many AI backends (Anthropic, DeepSeek, Google, Mistral, Ollama, OpenAI,\nvLLM, xAI, Z.ai) and is designed to make it easy to add more.\nUsers are never locked in to a single provider.\n\n### Bootstrapped development\nEach version of Humbug has been built using the previous version.\nThis means the software is both a product and a proof-of-concept: it demonstrates what\nhuman-AI collaboration can achieve at scale.\nOver 90% of the code has been written by LLMs working within Humbug itself.\n\n### Clean, modular architecture\nThe codebase is held to strict standards: mypy type checking, pylint linting, and a\ndependency rules system that prevents unwanted coupling between modules.\nThis discipline is what makes it possible for AIs to reliably modify and extend the code.\n\nThe dependency rules enforce a strict separation between top-level modules.\nThe dependency graph must be acyclic \u2014 no module may depend on another that depends (directly\nor transitively) on it.\nThis ensures each module can be reasoned about, tested, and evolved independently.\nIt also prevents the kind of gradual coupling that is especially risky when LLMs are\ncontributing code, since an AI might otherwise introduce a convenience import that silently\ncreates a circular dependency between modules.\n\n## What Humbug is NOT\n\n- **Not a replacement for the OS.** Humbug runs on top of Windows, macOS, and Linux\n  and provides OS-like abstractions without replacing the underlying system.\n- **Not just a developer tool.** While it has strong support for software development,\n  it is designed for any activity where humans and AIs need to work together.\n- **Not a walled garden.** It is open-source and designed to be extended.\n- **Not a single-AI system.** Multiple AI conversations can run simultaneously, with\n  support for task delegation between AI instances.\n\n## Menai: a language designed for AIs\n\nPreviously, programming languages were designed for human developers.\nWhile AIs are proficient with most of these languages, they can be unsafe because they\nsupport potentially dangerous I/O operations.\n\nMenai is a pure, functional, Lisp-inspired language designed specifically for AI use.\nBeing side-effect free, it requires no sandboxing and no user approval to execute.\nThis lets AIs build and run complex algorithmic tools freely and safely, without\ninterrupting the human collaborator.\n\nMenai supports higher-order functions, tail-call optimisation, strict numeric typing,\nand a rich standard library. It is compiled to bytecode and executed by a C VM for\nperformance, with a Python VM fallback.\n\n\n```",
      "completed": true,
      "tool_results": [
